Notes on the Draft
Style choices I made (matching the reference blogs):

Practitioner voice, first-person plural ("we"), grounded in a real story
Short paragraphs, no walls of text
Pull quotes / callouts for the key insights
Concrete sub-claims (5 layers of gates, 8 pipeline steps), not vague
Lessons-learned section near the end — readers love takeaways
No marketing fluff, no "revolutionary," no "transform your business"
Closing CTA links, like the reference posts have

Things you'll want to fill in / edit before submitting:

Your name, title
Specific numbers if you have them (# of DAOs, time saved, # of CLs generated, % of verification calls that self-healed). Even rough numbers ("dozens of DAOs," "hundreds of stubby calls") strengthen the post a lot
A quote from your TL or manager would land well — the reference posts both use them
One or two diagrams (the workflow diagrams from your project doc would be perfect — pipeline overview + verification self-heal loop)
Confirm Budget Manager is OK to name publicly; if not, generalize to "a Google service's data layer"


Submission Process — Step by Step
Since the editorial guidelines are at internal go/ links, here's how to actually move:

Read go/cloudwriting first. This is non-negotiable — it tells you which topic categories the team is currently prioritizing and which ones are saturated. Don't skip this; submissions that ignore the editorial calendar bounce.
Pick FastLane. Your post is a single-author, single-topic, technical-practitioner story from inside Google. That's exactly what FastLane is designed for. Editorial path is for big launches and complex, multi-stakeholder pieces.
Open the FastLane template at go/fastlanetemplate. Paste the draft above into it and reformat to match the template's section headers (they usually want: TL;DR, body, CTA, author bio, image specs).
Get internal review first. Before submitting:

Your manager / TL approves the content
Anyone you quote signs off on their quote
If you mention specific internal systems by name, confirm with the relevant team that the name is OK to use externally (Spanner is fine; internal codenames usually are not)
Take a quick pass for anything that should be generalized (specific QPS numbers, cost figures, internal team names)


Submit go/fastlaneintake. Fill out the form. Be specific in the "why this matters to readers" field — editors read that first to triage.
Expect editorial feedback. Editors will tighten the headline, possibly cut a section, and shepherd it through legal + PR review. Be ready for one or two rounds of revisions.
If they decline, they'll typically suggest the GCP Medium publication (go/cloud-medium). That's still a good outcome — the post lives in the official GCP Medium account and many readers find it there.
After publication, track performance at go/cgcBlogStats so you have data for your packet / promo case.


Quick Pre-submission Checklist

 Manager / TL approval on content
 Names of internal systems cleared for external use
 Numbers and metrics either included or explicitly cut
 Quotes (if any) signed off by the quoted person
 One or two diagrams attached (the workflow diagrams from your project docs work)
 Headline final
 Author bio (one sentence) ready
 Read through go/cloudwriting once
 FastLane template populated, intake form ready
